# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baker-valve-gear
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baker-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] The **AAR wheel arrangement** system is a method of classifying locomotive (or unit) wheel arrangements that was developed by the Association of American Railroads.
[src:baker-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] Essentially a simplification of the European UIC classification, it is widely used in North America to describe diesel and electric locomotives (including third-rail electric locomotives).
[src:baker-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] It is not used for steam locomotives anywhere, which use the Whyte notation instead, except geared steam locomotives, which are instead classified by their model and their number of trucks (bogies in Commonwealth English).
[src:baker-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] The AAR system (like UIC) counts axles, unlike Whyte notation, which counts wheels.
[src:baker-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] Letters refer to powered axles, with 'A' representing one powered axle, 'B' two consecutive powered axles on the same truck (bogie), 'C' three consecutive powered axles on the same truck, and so on.
[src:baker-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] Numbers are used to show unpowered (idler) axles.
[src:baker-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] "1" refers to one idler axle, and "2" to two idler axles in a row on the one truck (bogie), and so on.
[src:baker-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] A dash ("–") separates trucks (bogies) or wheel assemblies.
[src:baker-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] A plus sign ("+") refers to articulation, either by connecting bogies with span bolsters or by connecting individual locomotives via solid drawbars instead of couplers, or in multiple units, where each unit is permanently coupled to the other.
[src:baker-valve-gear/adams-axle] The **Adams axle** is a form of radial axle for rail locomotives that enable them to negotiate curves more easily.
[src:baker-valve-gear/adams-axle] It was invented by William Bridges Adams and patented in 1865.
[src:baker-valve-gear/adams-axle] The invention uses axle boxes that slide on an arc in shaped horn blocks, so allowing the axle to slide out to either side.
[src:baker-valve-gear/adams-axle] This is similar to the movement of a Bissell truck, but with the notional centre point of the curve being where the pivot of the truck would be.
[src:baker-valve-gear/adams-axle] This design, using slide bearings, is more expensive than one employing a shaft, but takes up less space.
[src:baker-valve-gear/adams-axle] Notwithstanding the 1865 comparative trials of the two inventors' products, there is some confusion over the inventor of the axle.
[src:baker-valve-gear/adams-axle] *Lexicon der Eisenbahn* cites William Adams (1823-1904) as the inventor.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Steam power has generally been superseded by the internal combustion engine or by electrical power drawn from an electrical grid.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The only steam installations that are in widespread use are the highly efficient thermal power plants used for generating electricity on a large scale.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] In contrast, the proposed steam engines may be for stationary, road, rail, or marine use.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Although most references to "Modern Steam" apply to developments since the 1970s, certain aspects of advanced steam technology can be discerned throughout the 20th century, notably automatic boiler control along with rapid startup.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] In 1922, Abner Doble developed an electro-mechanical system that reacted simultaneously to steam temperature and pressure, starting and stopping the feed pumps whilst igniting and cutting out the burner according to boiler pressure.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The contraflow monotube boiler had a working pressure of 750–1,200 psi (5.17–8.27 MPa) but contained so little water in circulation as to present no risk of explosion.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] This type of boiler was continuously developed in the US, Britain and Germany throughout the 1930s and into the 1950s for use in cars, buses, trucks, railcars, shunting locomotives (US; switchers), a speedboat and, in 1933, a converted Travel Air 2000 biplane.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] In the UK, Sentinel Waggon Works developed a vertical water-tube boiler running at 275 psi (1.90 MPa) which was used in road vehicles, shunting locomotives and railcars.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Steam could be raised much more quickly than with a conventional locomotive boiler.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Trials of the Anderson condensing system took place on Britain's Southern Railway between 1930 and 1935.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The Anderson condensing system uses a process known as mechanical vapor recompression.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] It was devised by a Glasgow marine engineer, Harry Percival Harvey Anderson.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The theory was that, by removing around 600 of the 970 British thermal units present in each pound of steam (1400 of the 2260 kilojoules in each kilogram), it would be possible to return the exhaust steam to the boiler by a pump which would consume only 1–2% of the engine's power output.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Between 1925 and 1927 Anderson, and another Glasgow engineer John McCullum (some sources give McCallum), conducted experiments on a stationary steam plant with encouraging results.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] A company, Steam Heat Conservation (SHC), was formed and a demonstration of Anderson's system was arranged at Surbiton Electricity Generating Station.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] SHC was interested in applying the system to a railway locomotive and contacted Richard Maunsell of the Southern Railway.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell requested that a controlled test be carried out at Surbiton and this was done about 1929.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell's technical assistant, Harold Holcroft, was present and a fuel saving of 29% was recorded, compared to conventional atmospheric working.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The Southern Railway converted SECR N class locomotive number A816 (later 1816 and 31816) to the Anderson system in 1930.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive underwent trials and initial results were encouraging.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The trials continued until 1934 but various problems arose, mostly with the fan for forced draught, and the project went no further.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive was converted back to standard form in 1935.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The work of French mechanical engineer André Chapelon in applying scientific analysis and a strive for thermal efficiency was an early example of advanced steam technology.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Chapelon's protégé Livio Dante Porta continued Chapelon's work.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Postwar in the late 1940s and 1950s some designers worked on modernising steam locomotives.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The Argentinian engineer Livio Dante Porta in the development of Stephensonian railway locomotives incorporating advanced steam technology was a precursor of the 'Modern Steam' movement from 1948.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Where possible, Porta much preferred to design new locomotives, but more often in practice he was forced to radically update old ones to incorporate the new technology.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] 1949 by Oliver Bulleid and the British Rail ‘Standard’ class steam locomotives of the 1950s by Robert Riddles, particularly the BR Standard Class 9F, were used to trial new steam locomotive design features, including the Franco-Crosti boiler.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] On moving to Ireland, Bulleid also designed CIÉ No.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The Sir Biscoe Tritton Lecture, given by Roger Waller, of the DLM company to the Institute of Mechanical Engineers in 2003 gives an idea of how problems in steam power are being addressed.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Waller refers mainly to some rack and pinion mountain railway locomotives that were newly built from 1992 to 1998.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] They were developed for three companies in Switzerland and Austria and continued to work on two of these lines as of 2008.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The new steam locomotives burn the same grade of light oil as their diesel counterparts, and all demonstrate the same advantages of ready availability and reduced labour cost; at the same time, they have been shown to greatly reduce air and ground pollution.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Their economic superiority has meant that they have largely replaced the diesel locomotives and railcars previously operating the line; additionally, steam locomotives are a tourist attraction.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] A parallel line of development was the return to steam power of the old Lake Geneva paddle steamer *Montreux* that had been refitted with a diesel-electric engine in the 1960s.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Economic aims similar to those achieved with the rack locomotives were pursued through automatic control of the light-oil-fired boiler and remote control of the engine from the bridge, enabling the steamship to be operated by a crew of the same size as a motor ship.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] A power unit based on advanced steam technology burning fossil fuel will inevitably emit carbon dioxide, a long-lasting greenhouse gas.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] However, significant reductions of other pollutants such as CO and NOx are achievable by steam compared to other combustion technologies, since it does not involve explosive combustion, thus removing the need for add-ons (such as filters) or special preparation of fuel.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] If renewable fuel such as wood or other biofuel is used then the system could be carbon neutral.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The use of biofuel remains controversial; however, liquid biofuels are easier to manufacture for steam plant than for diesels as they do not demand the stringent fuel standards required to protect diesel injectors.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] In principle, combustion and power delivery of steam plant can be considered separate stages.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] High overall thermal efficiency may be difficult to achieve, largely due to the extra stage of generating a working fluid between combustion and power delivery attributable mainly to leakages and heat losses.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The separation of the processes allows specific problems to be addressed at each stage without revising the whole system every time.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] For instance, the boiler or steam generator can be adapted to use any heat source, whether obtained from solid, liquid or gaseous fuel, and can use waste heat.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Whatever the choice, it will have no direct effect on the design of the engine unit, as that only ever has to deal with steam.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] This project mainly includes combined electrical generation and heating systems for private homes and small villages burning wood or bamboo chips.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] This is intended to replace 2-stroke donkey engines and small diesel power plants.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Drastic reduction in noise level is one immediate benefit of a steam-powered small plant.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Ted Pritchard, of Melbourne, Australia, was intensively developing this type of unit from 2002 until his death in 2007.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The company Pritchard Power (now Uniflow Power) stated in 2010 that they continue to develop the stationary S5000, and that a prototype had been built and was being tested, and designs were being refined for market ready products.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Until 2006 a German company called *Enginion* was actively developing a *Steamcell*, a micro CHP unit about the size of a PC tower for domestic use.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] It seems that by 2008 it had merged with Berlin company AMOVIS.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Since 2012, a French company, EXOES, is selling to industrial firms a Rankine Cycle, patented, engine, which is designed to work with many fuels such as concentrated solar power, biomass, or fossil.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The system, called "SHAPE" for Sustainable Heat And Power Engine, converts the heat into electricity.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The SHAPE engine is suitable for embedded, and stationary, applications.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] A SHAPE engine has been integrated into a biomass boiler, and into a Concentrated solar power system.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The company is planning to work with automobile manufactures, long-haul truck manufactures, and railway corporations.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] A similar unit is marketed by Powertherm, a subsidiary of Spilling (see below).
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] A company in India manufactures steam-powered generators in a range of sizes from 4 hp to 50 hp.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] They also offer a number of different mills that can be powered by their engines.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] In matter of technology, notice that the Quasiturbine is a uniflow rotary steam engine where steam intakes in hot areas, while exhausting in cold areas.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The Spilling company produces a variety of small fixed stationary plant adapted to biomass combustion or power derived from waste heat or pressure recovery.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The Finnish company Steammotor Finland has developed a small rotary steam engine that runs with 800 kW steam generator.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The engines are planned to produce electricity in wood chip fired power plants.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] According to the company, the steam engine named *Quadrum* generates 27% efficiency and runs with 180 °C steam at 8 bar pressure, while a corresponding steam turbine produces just 15% efficiency, requires steam temperature of 240 °C and pressure of 40 bar.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The high efficiency comes from a patented crank mechanism, that gives a smooth, pulseless torque.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The company believes that by further developing the construction there is potential to reach as high efficiency as 30–35%.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] During the first 1970s oil crisis, a number of investigations into steam technology were initiated by large automobile corporations although as the crisis died down, impetus was soon lost.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Australian engineer Ted Pritchard's main field of research from the late 1950s until the 1970s was the building of several efficient steam power units working on the uniflow system adapted to a small truck and two cars.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] One of the cars was achieving the lowest emissions figures of that time.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] All these engines made heavy use of flameless ceramic heat cells both for the steam generator and at strategic boost points where steam was injected into the cylinder(s).
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] A design mounted on power bogies with compact water-tube boiler similar to Sentinel designs of the 1930s.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Example: Sentinel-Cammell locomotive (right).
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Both 52 8055 and the proposed 5AT are of conventional layout, with the cab at the back, while the ACE 3000 had the cab located at the front.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Other approaches are possible, especially with liquid fuel firing.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] This is a well-tried design with the potential for a large power output and would provide the driver good visibility.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Another well-tried design with large power potential.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] A future design could include shorter water tanks, and a cab at each end, to give the driver a good view in either direction.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Another proposal for advanced steam technology is to revive the fireless locomotive, which runs on stored steam independently pre-generated.
[src:baker-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] An example is the Solar Steam Train project in Sacramento, California.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The **Arnoux system** is a train articulation system, for turning on railroad tracks, invented by Jean-Claude-Républicain Arnoux and patented in France in 1838.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Arnoux was the chief engineer of the Ligne de Sceaux, which was originally built with very tight radii in the area around Sceaux, Hauts-de-Seine.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] With the support of the French Academy of Sciences, Arnoux devised a new articulation system that allowed train wheels to turn, the *système ferroviaire dit Arnoux* ("Arnoux rail system"), and the Ligne de Sceaux was built to test his prototypes.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The line started commercial use in 1846, but the operating cost and the use of a broad gauge of 1,750 mm (5 ft 8+7⁄8 in) meant that it was not taken up more widely.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The invention of the bogie made it redundant.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] When railways were in their infancy, trains comprised a steam locomotive and one or more railway carriages with two fixed axles.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] As speeds increased, this design caused significant wear to the track and instability in the track ballast.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] To resolve these faults, Arnoux proposed a system of *essieux articulés* ("Articulated axles") where the yaw angle of the wheels was reduced to basically zero.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Arnoux adapted the system used on horse-carts, which pivoted each axle at its centre, to be applied equally over the two axles together.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Arnoux devised a system of chains and pulleys so that each of the wheels' correctly adjusted in yaw through the curve: as soon as the leading axle started to turn, all other axles would also turn by the same amount.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] However, this was flawed since not all carriages in a long train are on the same part of the curve.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] A compromise was to use pulleys of different diameters, with guide wheels on the locomotive to control their motion.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Also, using a broad gauge of 1,750 mm (5 ft 8+7⁄8 in) was expected to give greater stability.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] This system was not suitable for steam locomotives, so Arnoux invented a separate system for them.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The locomotives had a 2-4-2 wheel arrangement and the driving wheels were flangeless.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The carrying wheels were arranged to pivot and were controlled by near-horizontal guide wheels.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Arnoux applied for his patent, number 8342, on 28 March 1838.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Trials took place at Saint-Mandé between 1839 and 1840 in a 1 km (0.62 mi) circuit constructed by Alexis Dulong.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] These trials successfully demonstrated the stability and safety of the system.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Public bodies, the Duke of Aumale and numerous members of the French Academy of Sciences, including François Arago.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] After this experience, Arnoux was awarded the *Grand Prix de Mécanique* ("Grand Prize for Mechanical Engineering") by the Institute.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] At the suggestion of François Arago, the Arnoux system was implemented on the Ligne de Sceaux from Paris to Sceaux, Hauts-de-Seine.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] On 5 September 1844, Arnoux and the Minister of Public Works signed a contract to build and operate the line.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The line began service in 1846, starting from the *Barrière d'enfer* ("Hell's Gate") (see Denfert-Rochereau station) with a curved passenger building of 25-metre (82 ft) radius on a balloon loop to allow trains to reverse direction.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The route then had its first stop at Arcueil, then Bourg-la-Reine on a 30-metre (98 ft) radius curve.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The incline towards Sceaux was straight until the station at Fontenay-aux-Roses, then had a succession of curves at 63,-70-and-50-metre radii (207, 230 and 164 ft); the gradient was up to 11 mm/m (1.1%, 1:91), which was significant.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] All together the line was 10.5 km (6.5 mi) long.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The problem of curves was solved using bogies, which were invented in the United States shortly after adopting rail transport, but this was unknown in Europe at the time.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The Arnoux system bears some similarity to Cleminson's patent system, as both are designed to keep the axles radial to the curvature of the track.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Talgo utilises independent wheels mounted in a "rodal" between cars.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Linkage rods keep the "rodal" aligned tangentially with the track.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Like Arnoux, this system originally utilised (Iberian) broad gauge tracks, but recent versions are used on standard gauge or utilise variable gauge.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Current research may rework the Arnoux system by replacing its mechanical steering linkages with modern electronic systems.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The most promising approach places independent traction motors in each wheel which not only propel the vehicle but also steer the individual wheelset by means of torque vectoring.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] This gives reduced weight and complexity over current bogies whilst also reducing wear on both the train and track.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Examples include Actiwheel and their proposed running gear for the Next Generation Train.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The track was replaced overnight with standard gauge in May 1891.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] Woolf left Cornwall in 1785 to work for Joseph Bramah's engineering works in London.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] He worked there and at other firms as an engineer and engine builder until 1811 experimenting with high pressure steam and a much improved boiler.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] Michael Loam, who introduced the man engine to the UK, was trained by him.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] When he returned to Cornwall, beam engine designs were crude, shackled by outdated Watt patents and poor engineering, struggling to compete with large water wheels, even used underground.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] He learned from Bramah that to move forward meant adopting much improved engineering techniques, for it was Bramah who invented quality control.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] Woolf was chief engineer to Harvey & Co of Hayle, the leading engineering and foundry works, at this time the largest in the world.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] They eventually swallowed up the rival Copperhouse Foundry run by Sandys, Carne and Vivian.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] For very many years they were the leading firm worldwide for drainage engines, even supplying three eight-beamed pumping engines to the Dutch government to drain the Haarlemmermeer (see Museum De Cruquius).
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] By the time Woolf retired in 1836 the Cornish engine, owing largely to his efforts, was a thing of magnificent beauty and efficiency.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] In 1803, Woolf obtained a patent on an improved boiler for producing high pressure steam.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] In 1804, he patented his best-known invention, a compound steam engine.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] Woolf's engine was a parallel compound engine with two cylinders in which the steam worked in succession.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] These were both coupled to the same end of the beam of the engine.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] The operation of the engine can be described as being a high-pressure cylinder of Trevithick's high-pressure simple expansion engine, followed by a condensing cylinder of Watt's design.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] Woolf had worked as an engine erector for Hornblower and was familiar with his earlier work on compound engines.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] As a Cornishman, he was also familiar with Trevithick and his newly developed high-pressure 'puffer' engines that were then entering service.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] He recognised that, even with the new principle of expansion, the exhaust from a Trevithick engine was still of a pressure comparable to the inlet pressure of a Watt engine.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] From this step, it was a relatively simple matter to couple the two.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] For most uses, the cylinders of the engine were double-acting.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] Opposing sides of the high- and low-pressure cylinders were cross-connected to each other.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] Where engines were used for pumping, Woolf engines were also built with paired single-acting cylinders.
[src:baker-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] Examples of Woolf compound rotative beam engines may be seen at Abbey Pumping Station, Blagdon Lake, Claymills Pumping Station, The Hamilton Museum of Steam & Technology, and the Western Springs Pumphouse, now part of the Museum of Transport and Technology Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] A **bogie** (/ˈboʊɡi/ *BOH-ghee*) (or **truck** in North American English) comprises two or more wheelsets (two wheels on an axle), in a frame, attached under a vehicle by a pivot.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Bogies take various forms in various modes of transport.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] A bogie may remain normally attached (as on many railroad cars and semi-trailers) or be quickly detachable (as for a dolly in a road train or in railway bogie exchange).
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] It may include suspension components within it (as most rail and trucking bogies do), or be solid and, in turn, be suspended (as are most bogies of tracked vehicles).
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] It may be mounted on a swivel, as traditionally on a railway carriage or locomotive, additionally jointed and sprung (as in the landing gear of an airliner), or held in place by other means (centreless bogies).
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Although *bogie* is the preferred spelling and first-listed variant in various dictionaries, **bogey** and **bogy** are also used.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] A *bogie* in the UK, or a *railroad truck*, *wheel truck*, or *truck* in North America, is a structure underneath a railway vehicle (wagon, coach, or locomotive) to which axles (hence, wheels) are attached through bearings.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] In Indian English, *bogie* may also refer to an entire railway carriage.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] In South Africa, the term *bogie* is often alternatively used to refer to a freight or goods wagon (shortened from *bogie wagon*).
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The bogie was independently invented in the UK and the USA to address different problems.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The first locomotive with a bogie was built by UK engineer William Chapman in 1812.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] However, there was no great demand because railroads in the UK at the time tended to be very straight, which British engineers saw as the most efficient way to get between two points.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] In the USA, the terrain was more challenging, and curved lines were a necessity.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The bogie was first used in America for horse-drawn wagons on the Quincy Granite Railroad in 1829.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The first successful locomotive with a bogie to guide the locomotive into curves while also supporting the smokebox was built by John B.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] This led to a whole new *form* of rail car that, like those of which are recognizable today, are long cars, not the short stagecoach cars (example) which were initially required to keep the distance between axles short.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] These long cars carry more weight because the eight wheels distribute the load, smooth out the ride due to the independent suspension, and reduce friction on curves.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The B&O railroad, with which Winans contracted, was the first to adopt bogie rail cars in the 1830s.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] It took a while for the "American" style car to catch on in England.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The first use of bogie coaches in Britain was in 1872 by the Festiniog Railway.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The first standard-gauge British railway to build coaches with bogies, instead of rigidly mounted axles, was the Midland Railway in 1874.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Instability can occur when a combination of bogie design, springing, vehicle and bogie wheelbase, and track dynamics, causes the bogie to oscillate at high speed – a phenomenon known as "hunting".
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Cars exhibiting hunting are removed immediately upon discovery of the defect.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] A tendency for more than one vehicle to hunt will result in investigations with a view to re-designing.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Usually, two bogies are fitted to each carriage, wagon or locomotive, one at each end.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Another configuration is often used in articulated vehicles, in which the bogies (often Jacobs bogies) are placed under the connection between the carriages or wagons.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Most bogies have two axles, but some cars designed for superior riding qualities or heavy loads have more axles per bogie.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Heavy-duty cars may have more than two bogies using span bolsters to equalize the load and connect the bogies to the cars.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Usually, the train floor is at a level above the bogies, but the floor of the area between the bogies may be lowered to increase interior space while staying within height restrictions.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Examples are container well cars, bi-level passenger cars, or stepless-entry, low-floor cars on railways with near-ground-level platforms.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The bogie's connections to the rail vehicle allow a certain degree of rotation about a vertical-axis pivot (bolster), with side bearers preventing excessive movement.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] More modern, bolsterless bogie designs omit these features, instead taking advantage of the sideways movement of the suspension to permit rotational movement.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Modern diesel and electric locomotives are mounted on bogies.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Those commonly used in North America include Type A, Blomberg, HT-C, and Flexicoil trucks.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] On a steam locomotive, the leading and trailing wheels may be mounted on bogies like Bissel trucks (also known as *pony trucks*).
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Articulated locomotives (e.g., Fairlie, Garratt or Mallet locomotives) have **power bogies** similar to those on diesel and electric locomotives.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] A rollbock is a specialized type of bogie that is inserted under the wheels of a rail wagon/car, usually to convert to another track gauge.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Transporter wagons apply the same concept at the level of a flatcar specialized to carry other cars as its load.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] In archbar or diamond frame bogies, the side frames are fabricated rather than cast.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Tram bogies are much simpler in design because of their axle load, and the tighter curves found on tramways mean tram bogies seldom have more than two axles.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Furthermore, some tramways have steeper gradients and vertical as well as horizontal curves, which means tram bogies often need to pivot on the horizontal axis, as well.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Some articulated trams have bogies located under the articulations, a setup known as a Jacobs bogie.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Often, low-floor trams are fitted with nonpivoting bogies; many tramway enthusiasts see this as a retrograde step, as it leads to greater wear on both track and wheels and significantly reduces the speed at which a tram can round a curve.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] In the past, many different types of bogies (trucks) have been used under tramcars (e.g., Brill, Peckham, maximum traction).
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] A maximum traction truck has one driving axle with large wheels and one non-driving axle with smaller wheels.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The bogie pivot is located off-centre, so more than half the weight rests on the driving axle.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The retractable stadium roof on Toronto's Rogers Centre used modified off-the-shelf train bogies on a circular rail.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The system was chosen for its proven reliability.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Rubber-tyred metro trains use a specialised version of railway bogies.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Special flanged steel wheels are behind the rubber-tired running wheels, with additional horizontal guide wheels in front and behind them.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The unusually large flanges on the steel wheels guide the bogie through standard railroad switches, and in addition keep the train from derailing in case the tires deflate.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] To overcome breaks of gauge, some bogies are being fitted with variable gauge axles (VGA) so that they can operate on two different gauges.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] These include the SUW 2000 system from ZNTK Poznań.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Radial-steering trucks, also known as radial bogies, allow the individual axles to align with curves in addition to the bogie frame pivoting as a whole.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] For non-radial bogies, the more axles in the assembly, the more difficulty it has negotiating curves, due to wheel flange to rail friction.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] For radial bogies, the wheelsets actively steer through curves, thereby reducing wear at the wheel's flange-to-rail interface and improving adhesion.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] In the US, radial steering has been implemented in EMD and GE locomotives.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The EMD version, designated HTCR, was made standard equipment for the SD70 series, first sold in 1993.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The HTCR in operation had mixed results and relatively high purchase and maintenance costs.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] EMD subsequently introduced the HTSC truck, essentially the HTCR stripped of radial components.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] GE introduced their version in 1995 as a buyer option for the AC4400CW and later Evolution Series locomotives.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] However, it also met with limited acceptance because of its relatively high purchase and maintenance costs, and customers have generally chosen GE Hi-Ad standard trucks for newer and rebuilt locomotives.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] A 19th-century configuration of self-steering axles on rolling stock established the principle of radial steering.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The Cleminson system involved three axles, each mounted on a frame that had a central pivot; the central axle could slide transversely.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The three axles were connected by linkages that kept them parallel on the straight and moved the end ones radially on a curve, so that all three axles were continually at right angles to the rails.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The configuration, invented by British engineer John James Davidge Cleminson, was first granted a patent in the UK in 1883.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The system was widely used on British narrow-gauge rolling stock, such as on the Isle of Man and Manx Northern Railways.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The Holdfast Bay Railway Company in South Australia, which later became the Glenelg Railway Company, purchased Cleminson-configured carriages in 1880 from the American Gilbert & Bush Company for its 1600 mm (5 ft 3 in) broad-gauge line.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] An **articulated bogie** (aka Jakob-type) is any one of several bogie designs that reduce weight, increase passenger comfort, and allow railway equipment to safely turn sharp corners, while reducing or eliminating the "screeching" normally associated with metal wheels rounding a bend in the rails.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] There are several such designs, and the term is also applied to train sets that incorporate articulation within the vehicle, rather than in the bogies themselves.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] If one considers a single bogie "up close", it resembles a small railcar with axles at either end.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] The same effect that causes the bogies to rub against the rails at a longer radius causes each of the pairs of wheels to rub on the rails and cause the screeching.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Articulated bogies add a second pivot point between the two axles (wheelsets) to allow them to rotate to the correct angle even in these cases.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Some tanks and other tracked vehicles have bogies as external suspension components (see armoured fighting vehicle suspension).
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] This type of bogie usually has two or more road wheels and a sprung suspension to smooth the ride over rough terrain.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Bogie suspensions keep many of their components on the outside of the vehicle, saving internal space.
[src:baker-valve-gear/articulated-bogie] Although vulnerable to antitank fire, they can often be repaired or replaced in the field.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] After about 1910, the **Baker valve gear** was the main competitor to Walschaerts valve gear for steam locomotives in the United States.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] Strictly speaking it was not a valve gear but a variable expansion mechanism adapted to the Walschaerts layout replacing the expansion link and sliding die block.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] The Baker arrangement used more pivot bearings or *pin joints*, but avoided the die slip inherent to the expansion link, with the aim of lessening wear and the need for service; it could also facilitate longer valve travel.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] In the early 1900s there were many efforts to create a new valve gear to replace the by-then-standard Walschaerts valve gear.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] In the United States the Young, Southern, Caprotti and Franklin patterns were used on a few classes, but only the Baker pattern won more than limited acceptance.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] Baker Company, of Swanton, Ohio; a builder of steam traction engines.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] The idea came from an employee called Gifford but was developed by the Baker company with the first patents being issued in 1903 and with patents issued through at least November, 1912.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] The Baker Locomotive Valve Gear was produced by the Pilliod Co. of Swanton, Ohio.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] Subsequent versions were produced up to the end of steam service.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] It was particularly popular on the Norfolk and Western Railway, and almost all later N&W engines used it.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] Other extensive users included the Chesapeake and Ohio Railway, the Nickel Plate Road, the New York Central Railroad and the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] There was always debate about the advantages of Baker gear, the main criticism being the number of pin joints and possible lost motion.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] While popular with railroads on the east, western states tended to continue with the Walschaerts pattern.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] In Britain, Baker gear was popular amongst model engineers but in full-size practice the length of the yoke and the width of the assembly may have been difficult to accommodate within the restricted loading gauge.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] Other locomotives to use Baker valve gear were the New Zealand Railways J class, Ja class, Jb class, some Ka class, and the South Australian Railways 620 class.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] The Baker valve gear replaces the expansion link of the Walschaerts gear with an assembly of levers and links which produces the same effect of allowing continuous variation valve travel.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] The remainder of the gear is the same, so that the return crank and combination lever take the same form, although the proportions are usually modified.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] The Pilliod Co. sold the gear as a single assembly which was mounted on the frame in the location ordinarily occupied by the Walschaerts expansion link.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] The parts were arranged so that when the yoke was centered, the connection of the main link to the bellcrank was in a line with the two pivots on the yoke.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] At this point, the back and forth motion of the lower end of the main link left the top relatively motionless as main link swung back and forth on the swing links.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] In forward motion, the yoke was pushed forward, so that its upper pivot was in front of the bell crank-main link connection.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] Moving the eccentric arm back and forth lowered and raised the top of the main link.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] This motion was translated by the bellcrank into back and forth motion of the radius rod.
[src:baker-valve-gear/baker-valve-gear] The angle of the yoke controlled the relative motion, and therefore the cutoff; tilting the yoke backwards reversed the motion of the radius rod.
